<li>Leonard, Nick, 2016, &ldquo;Testimony, evidence and interpersonal
reasons,&rdquo; <em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 173:
2333&ndash;2352.</li>

<li>Leydon-Hardy, Lauren, 2021, &ldquo;Predatory grooming and
epistemic infringement,&rdquo; in J. Lackey, ed., <em>Applied
Epistemology</em> Oxford: Oxford University Press, 119&ndash;147.</li>

<li>List, Christian &amp; Pettit, Philip, 2002, &ldquo;Aggregating
sets of judgments: an impossibility result,&rdquo; <em>Economics and
Philosophy</em>, 18: 89&ndash;110.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2011, <em>Group Agency: The Possibility,
Design, and Status of Corporate Agents</em>, Oxford: Oxford University
Press. doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199591565.001.0001</li>

<li>Locke, John, 1690, <em>An Essay Concerning Human
Understanding</em>, London.</li>

<li>Longino, Helen E., 1990, <em>Science as Social Knowledge: Values
and Objectivity in Scientific Inquiry</em>, Princeton, NJ: Princeton
University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2002. <em>The Fate of Knowledge</em>,
Princeton, NJ: Princeton University Press.</li>

<li>Lopez-Guerra, Claudio, 2010, &ldquo;The Enfranchisement
Lottery,&rdquo; <em>Politics, Philosophy, and Economics</em> 10(2):
211&ndash;233.</li>

<li>Lynch, Michael, 2018, "Epistemic Arrogance and Political Dissent." <em>In Voicing Dissent</em>. New York: Routledge.</li>

<li>Maitra, Ishani, 2018, &ldquo;New words for old wrongs,&rdquo;
<em>Episteme</em>, 15(3): 345&ndash;362.</li>

<li>Malmgren, Anna-Sara, 2006, &ldquo;Is There A Priori Knowledge by
Testimony?,&rdquo; <em>The Philosophical Review</em>, 115(2):
199&ndash;241.</li>

<li>Mason, Rebecca, 2011, &ldquo;Two Kinds of Unknowing,&rdquo;
<em>Hypatia</em>, 26(2): 294&ndash;307.</li>

<li>Mayo-Wilson, Conor, Zollman, Kevin J. S., &amp; David Danks,
2011, &ldquo;The Independence Thesis: When Individual and Social
Epistemology Diverge,&rdquo; <em>Philosophy of Science</em>, 78(4):
653&ndash;677. doi:10.1086/661777</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, &ldquo;Wisdom of Crowds versus
Groupthink: Learning in Groups and in Isolation,&rdquo;
<em>International Journal of Game Theory</em>, 42(3): 695&ndash;723.
doi:10.1007/s00182-012-0329-7</li>

<li>McKinnon, Rachel, 2017, &ldquo;Gaslighting as epistemic
injustice,&rdquo; in Kidd, I., Medina, J., and Pohlhaus, G., eds.,
<em>The Routledge Handbook of Epistemic Injustice</em>, New York:
Routledge, 167&ndash;174.</li>

<li>McMyler, Benjamin, 2011, <em>Testimony, trust, and
authority</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Medina, Jos&eacute;, 2011, &ldquo;The relevance of credibility
excess in a proportional view of epistemic injustice: Differential
epistemic authority and the social imaginary,&rdquo; <em>Social
Epistemology</em>, 25(1): 15&ndash;35.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2012, <em>The Epistemology of Resistance:
Gender and Racial Oppression, Epistemic Injustice, and the Social
