<li>Merton, Robert K., 1968, &ldquo;The Matthew Effect in Science:
The Reward and Communication Systems of Science Are Considered,&rdquo;
<em>Science</em>, 159(3810): 56&ndash;63.
doi:10.1126/science.159.3810.56</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1973, <em>The Sociology of Science:
Theoretical and Empirical Investigations</em>, Chicago: University of
Chicago Press.</li>

<li>Meyer, M., Alfano, M., and De Bruin, B., 2021, &ldquo;Epistemic
vice predicts acceptance of Covid-19 misinformation,&rdquo;
<em>Episteme</em>: 1&ndash;22.</li>

<li>Mill, John Stuart, 1859 [1966], <em>On Liberty</em>, London.
Reprinted in his <em>A Selection of His Works</em>, John M. Robson
ed., London: Palgrave, 1966, 1&ndash;147.</li>

<li>Miller, Richard, 2020, &ldquo;The Epistemology of Plea
Bargaining,&rdquo; <em>Social Epistemology</em>, 34(5):
501&ndash;512</li>

<li>Mills, Charles, 1997, <em>The Racial Contract</em>, Ithaca, NY:
Cornell University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2007, &ldquo;White Ignorance,&rdquo; in
Shannon Sullivan &amp; Nancy Tuana, eds., <em>Race and Epistemologies
of Ignorance</em>, Albany: State Univ of New York Press,
11&ndash;38.</li>

<li>Mongin, P., 2008, &ldquo;Factoring Out the Impossibility of
Logical Aggregation,&rdquo;<em>Journal of Economic Theory</em>, 141:
100&ndash;113.</li>

<li>Moody-Adams, Michelle, 1994, &ldquo;Culture, Responsibility, and
